http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/Five-more-held-in-fake-note-racket-in-Prakasam/article13978473.ece

Prakasam police on Saturday arrested five more persons in connection with Fake Indian Currency Notes (FICN) racket with suspected links with gangs from Bangladesh.Producing before the media the gangsters who had allegedly put into circulation FICN of Rs. 1,000 and Rs. 500 denomination for Rs. 47 lakh in Krishna, Anantapur and Prakasam districts here, Kandukur Deputy Superintendent of Police V. Srinivasa Rao said probe revealed that the gangsters had collected the FICN from their associates in Odisha and circulated them in gambling dens, bars and restaurants, hotels and fuel filling stations in the three districts.Police are on the lookout for three more persons, including one from Jharkhand, who had exchanged the FICN for currency notes in the ratio of 100: 40 with their counterparts here.Those arrested near Thetu in Prakasam district were one Shankar Naik from Telangana, G. Ravi (36) from Dharmavaram in Anantapur district, G.Nagaraju (36), P.Sridhar (39) and B.Srinath (31), all hailing from Anantapur town.Five FICN with face value of Rs. 1,000 and 40 FICN with face value of Rs. 500 were recovered from them, Prakasam Central Crime Station DSP K. Venkateswara Rao said. The arrest came close on the heels of nabbing eight members of the gangsters operating from the three districts on December 22.“It is not easily possible to identify fake notes by the layman,” the DSP said, adding the gangsters had faked the latest series of Rs. 1,000 and Rs. 500 notes printed by the Reserve Bank of India, he added.Except for some shortcomings in the colour of the security thread, the fake notes carried almost all the security features that are found in the genuine currency notes, including the portrait of Mahatma Gandhi and the year of printing, the DSP said. They could be detected only by fake note detector machine.